              <div class="quotetitle">sowellfan wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Well, I guess the first question is, &quot;Do you want to be an engineer?&quot; Obviously if you want to get a PE license at some point, then this isn't the school for you. But I think lots of other places that hire &quot;engineers&quot;, even without the PE license requirement, would balk at the non-ABET accreditation.<br /><br />On the other hand, if you're looking to work in some sort of field where you're not expected to be an engineer, but maybe more of a robotics/electronics guru, it might be reasonable to stay in that program.<br /><br />What sort of places are you thinking about working?</div><br /><br />I do indeed want to be an engineer. UVA is a real university, they have accreditation per the ABET site for all their traditional programs, specifically EE, CE, and ME. The program I am participating in is made up of classes from those accredited programs. The quality side is their.<br /><br />So, it is of your opinion that the ABET matters for many places? Most places even? <br /><br />There is a port here, a regional airport, etc. There are some manufacturing firms, but still, most shops are Navy contractors. The big guys mostly all have some presence. BAE is nearby, HP has contracts, Northrup Grunman.

              

              
              
