              <div class="quotetitle">heatpackinyum wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I would imagine that UVA is going to be enough to get you in the door, regardless of accreditation status.<br /><br />That said, if you have even the slightest hint that you're ever going to want or need a PE, <a href="http://www.ncees.org/Licensure.php" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">do not pass go, do not collect $200</a>.<br /><br />Personally (says the random [not totally random; I am an ME, and work has indicated that they would indeed like me to pursue a PE] guy on the internet), I wouldn't do it. ABET accreditation for engineering schools is so widespread (not that it's a simple gimme; their auditors were thorough when they went through our engineering program, and that was clear just via observation and hearsay from the professors) that not having an accredited degree would make me uncomfortable unless I knew that I was going to be in some field that would never require it. As noted in my opening sentence, the fact that the school is UVA changes the equation a bit, but given that my immediate reaction would have been a resounding &quot;no&quot; had it been anything but a well-regarded school, I'm inclined to go with the gut reaction.<br /><br />Are we correct in assuming that this would be an undergraduate degree?</div><br /><br />Yes, it's a Bachelors. The combination of Good School, and extreme convenience are the two big pros for me. <br /><br />I'd have to drive 30 or so minutes to campus if I were to opt instead for Old Dominion University. I lose name recognition, but they are by no means fly by night. IIRC, they were the engineering branch of William and Mary at one point. And of course ABET. <br /><br />Does anyone have any experience with Engineering Science? I've been in Military contracting long enough to have a fair idea what an EE or an ME or even a CE looks like. ES? Not so clear to me.

              

              
              
