          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Even if you never plan to get your PE, I would stick with an acredited school. ABET acredidation will mean more than the school you got your degree from. <br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Pysgard wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I do indeed want to be an engineer. UVA is a real university, they have accreditation per the ABET site for all their traditional programs, specifically EE, CE, and ME. The program I am participating in is made up of classes from those accredited programs. The quality side is their.<br /><br />So, it is of your opinion that the ABET matters for many places? Most places even? <br /><br />There is a port here, a regional airport, etc. There are some manufacturing firms, but still, most shops are Navy contractors. The big guys mostly all have some presence. BAE is nearby, HP has contracts, Northrup Grunman.</div><br /><br />Those companies are most likely going to require ABET certification. The &quot;job&quot; may not require any actual real engineering, but I can almost guarantee you will need ABET to get your foot in the door if you apply for any position requiring an engineering degree. Doesn't matter how good the school is, if the program is not accredited your degree will be worth less. I'm not saying you won't be able to get an engineering job, but that first job will be a lot tougher to acquire. I could be wrong, but at the very least I would see what they require now. Pretend you are looking for a job and see what is needed.<br /><br />If you were already working as an engineer and were just trying to get a degree to back up your experience I'd be more positive, but you will be limiting your future prospects without the accredidation.<br /><br />I did a quick search at Northrop-Grumman and found this for EE level 1,<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">In order to be considered for this position, candidates must have completed their degree from an accredited college or university within the last twelve (12) months.  Additionally, they will have no more than one (1) year of relevant work experience.  Northrop Grumman will consider all recent qualified college graduates, regardless of age.</div><br /><br />I looked at a few of the software positions and I did not see an acredidation requirement.<br /><br />For ME level 3<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">A Bachelors or Masters degree in Mechanical Engineering is required with 3-5 years of experience.</div><br /><br />Wether they check if you have an acredited degree,  <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/confused.gif" alt=":confused:" title="Confused" /> <br /><br />Personally I wouldn't work for a company that can't design a web site that can handle the back button.  <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/big_grin.png" alt=":D" title="Big Green" />

              

              
              
            </div>
