              Why bother with an unaccredited program and one that by its own admission will never get such a thing?<br /><br />It's not like there's any lack of comparable schools that are accredited.<br /><br />I don't know how many employers check for that sort of thing, but if even 10 per cent do, it could include the outfit you really want to work for.<br /><br />Degrees follow you around for a long time.  I changed jobs twice in my 50s and the first thing I had to deal with in terms of the HR gauntlet was my degree transcripts.  My hiring manager didn't care half as much as HR, but in big companies, HR can <span style="font-style: italic">veto</span> if they don't like the answers they get.<br /><br />There's a lot of &quot;checkmark-ism&quot; especially at big companies.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I know who got their PE's are civil engineers working on buildings/roads<br /></div><br /><br />My brother is a mechanical engineer, and he got his PE.  He worked (still works) in the steel industry.

              

              
              
