          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Still, as was pointed out earlier a lot of employers will have words in job requisitions that require a degree from an ABET accredited program. One problem with some of these types of curricula are that there's no lab time. That's not great for an engineering degree. Probably a major reason why it would not be accredited. <br /></div><br /><br />If true, that's a substantive problem.  I wouldn't take any kind of engineering degree that short-circuited the hands-on part.<br /><br />Not only is it bad for prep, it isn't even helpful when you start interviewing for jobs.  In any sort of engineering discipline, they're going to expect you to have worked on projects of some sort.<br /><br />OP:  Find out <span style="font-style: italic">what's missing</span> as a matter of actual, specific fact; be it labs or something else.  There's more to it than &quot;we can't get accredited and don't plan to.&quot;  <span style="font-style: italic">Why</span> may be important to you.  There's an argument going on here.  You need to see behind the result to the underlying causes.

              

              
              
            </div>
