        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Looking at the website linked by the OP, and their <a href="http://www.seas.virginia.edu/acad/programs/producedinva/engsci.php" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Engineering Science</a> page, this program seems to be an odd hybrid of basic core from community college classes, followed by a &quot;double minor&quot; of proper engineering courses from UVA, with some added specialization and a senior thesis-type project. While I kind of see what they're going for, and I think you could do just fine in a career based on that coursework, I don't actually see much advantage to be had there relative to what could be achieved within a conventional e.g. mechanical engineering program with appropriately-selected electives, and possibly a community-college transfer process if those cost vs. time tradeoffs were appealing. <br /><br /><br />Honestly the ABET accreditation process has always been a bit unclear to me. At my school the mechanical engineering degree had for decades been listed as a B.S. in &quot;Engineering and Applied Science&quot; with a concentration in mechanical engineering. This program was accredited. My senior year, they reshuffled some stuff in the course catalog and created a B.S. in Mechanical Engineering, with the same coursework requirements as the previous program. This is the degree I received. However, since it was the first year of the program, technically the ABET accreditation process had not been completed at the time I received my degree... but maybe there's some kind of retroactive accreditation granted? I'm sure I could argue it successfully if it was challenged, but I've never been completely confident where it stands.<br /><br />As far as the PE licensing goes, the vast majority of the mechanical engineers I've worked with do not have one, and I don't really see a need for it in most trajectories I can see my career taking... though I would like to go through the process and get the license one of these years, just for its own sake. On the other hand, my wife works at a civil engineering consulting company, and with her Environmental <span style="font-weight: bold">Science</span> degrees she has been hampered in advancement somewhat, because of the way PE licensure is baked into the company's advancement policies and employee grade-level descriptions. Not all companies are like that, but it's a concern worth keeping in mind.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
