        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle">PsionEdge wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I did a little looking into info about the PE and basically since the licensing is regulated at the state level if you work on products that could be sold across state lines a PE license is not required. So it makes sense that the only people that seem to need them are those working civil engineering projects and construction sites/buildings..</div><br /><br />It sounds like you're convinced that you're not going into an industry that requires one, but this isn't entirely correct; you are indeed licensed by a state, but since everybody takes the same tests administered by the NCEES, nearly every state has reciprocity (I've also heard them called &quot;comity&quot;) agreements with every other state. Thus you get licensed in state A and for a fee and a chunk of verification data, you can get a license in states B, C, and D as well. Thus we have old guys with licenses from seven different states on their wall (this mainly applies to the old onshore guys, as offshore design just requires a stamp from the state in which your firm is registered).<br /><br />/end derail<br /><br />For whatever it is worth, I'd second the advice calling for an ABET accredited degree; I interned at a defense contractor and was told &quot;lol, PE?&quot; time and again, but ended up in a different industry (I'm an ME). Just because you don't need one now doesn't mean you never will (particularly in a boom/bust industry like defense traditionally is).

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
